title: For Sale/Trade:  Collectible Enfield pistol
postcontent:
This is a British Enfield Number 2, Mark 1 .38-caliber revolver from World War II. The action (DAO) is very tight and completely functional. The black finish is original, complete, and without flaw. The original Bakelite grips are in immaculate condition. The cartridge ejector works fine and the barrel's grooves are still visible. Overall, this pistol would easily rate at 95%.

This webpage has some detailed history of the pistol: http://www.nrvoutdoors.com/ENFIELD%20SNUB/ENFIELD%20SNUB.htm. In the first photograph on the left margin (with the red velvet background), my pistol is almost identical to the one in the middle. However, my pistol has the distinction of having a factory-installed lanyard loop in the frame at the base of the grip, similar to the pre-WWII pistol pictured at the top. Research shows that this feature is quite rare and indicates that this particular pistol was a British officer's pistol which would have seen little, if any, battlefield usage, probably accounting for this pistol's pristine condition.

Provenance from the early 1960s can be provided. The original Hunter leather holster is included in this sale as well as three (3) new 50-round boxes of .38 S&W Remington Express cartridges. Attached are photographs of my actual pistol.

My price is $750 cash negotiable or will trade straight-up for any of the below listed pistols. Email me if you're interested. Thanks!

title: For Sale:  Olympic Arms OA-93 Carbine - Collector's Item - Rare
postcontent:
For sale is collector item - This is a lightly used Olympic Arms OA-93 Carbine in 5.56mm with folding stock, 3-9x32 scope, original Oly Arms grip with storage compartment, and a stamped OA-93 lower receiver (not M.F.R.) made in 1999. 

The now discontinued OA-93 Carbine was an inovative design that placed the buffer assembly on top of the upper, allowing for the use of a side folding stock, much like the AK-47. Unfortunately, low sales at the time caused the discontinuing of the line. 

The lower receiver is post ban when Oly Arms, in answer to high demand for AR-15s, took some of the pre ban OA-93 pistol lowers off the shelf to make rifles after the restricitons from the Clinton Assault Weapons ban went away. Note the steel inserts at the front takedown pin. The OA-93 pistols had a larger front takedown lug on the upper to keep people from changing between pistols and rifles by switching uppers. I believe Oly Arms stopped making the OA-93 carbine around 2009. 

This rifle test fired flawlessly and functions very smoothly. Overall length with stock extended - 36.25", with stock folded - 28".  More pictures available.

title: For Sale:  Very Rare M1892 Colt US Army
postcontent:
This is a 100% original, unaltered 1892 .38 Colt US Army.  Out of the 8000 of these revolvers contracted for the US military, nearly all were modified with an internal cylinder lock and a lanyard ring.  This gun has no such modifications.  All serial numbers match and all cartouchings are intact and correct.  From the serial number, this gun is a first year issue (manufactured in 1892) and inspected by Captain David M Taylor in 1893.

From research that I've found, which is few and far between, there are very few known examples of unmodified 1892's.  Truly a once in a lifetime find!  85% overall condition.   Anyone with additional information that they're willing to share with me about this gun please do!

Absolutely firm on the price.  Thanks for viewing!

Here is a link to some information I've found on this gun:  

http://www.coltforum.com/forums/colt-revolvers/32194-model-1892-serial-numbers.html


Here is a link to another 1892 that looks pretty rough and has been modified with the cylinder lock but no lanyard ring.  It reaffirms my research.

http://www.antiquearmsinc.com/colt-model-1892-double-action-revolver-new-army-navy-cavalry-us-model-1892-1894-1895-1889-span-am.htm

Here is yet another with a cylinder lock, no lanyard ring, but the model numbers sanded off of the butt of the gun: (very common)

http://www.1898andb-4.com/products.php?pid=767&detail=true

UPDATE:  If you're not willing to pay $4,000, please don't bother contacting me to purchase it.  I am not a pawn shop and for those thinking that I am over-priced, I guarantee won't find another one for sale.  I challenge you to find another!

In fact if you find another one, send me the link and I'll buy that one too.  You cannot gauge this gun against a modified, run of the mill Colt 1892.  You just can't...   Thank you.
